<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-12-05T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-12-05T12:00:00-05:00" n="393" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d393">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94 Commission/604: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Acting Chairman of the American Delegation to the General
                                Disarmament Conference (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_GHS1" type="to">Gibson</persName>)</hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-12-05T12:00:00-05:00">December 5,
                                1932—noon</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>45. For <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_DNH1">Davis</persName> and
                                <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_WHR1">Wilson</persName>. Your 56,
                            December 4, 10 p.m., and Department’s 44, December 4, midnight. I concur
                            in your estimate and in your conclusions set forth in penultimate
                            paragraph.</p>
                        <p>I approve of your talking strictly confidentially in your discretion with
                            chief delegates of Great Britain and France as suggested in concluding
                            paragraph.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_SHL1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>